[Experiment 7] - Mediators | Linear relationships

library(dagitty)
library(ggdag)
library(tibble)
library(purrr)

Mediators (linear)

The target of this experiment is to check if mediators can be used to solve problems with confounding when not having confounder data, and how to do it for linear problems.

Steps of the experiment:

  1. Define causal model with an mediator variable (M) and a confounder (U)
  2. Create dataset based on the defined causal model.
  3. Try to estimate the influence of X on Y without knowing M nor U. This is the traditional machine learning approach and should fail.
  4. Try to estimate the influence of X on Y knowing M but not U. Is this possible?
  5. Try to estimate the influence of X on Y knowing the confounder U. We have already seen this works.

1. Define causal model

Lets define a very simple model with a mediator variable (M) and a confounder (U). We will use

dag <- dagify(Y ~ M,
              M ~ X,
              X ~ U,
              Y ~ U,
              coords = data.frame(x = c(0, 1, .5, .5), 
                                  y = c(0, 0, 0, 1), 
                                  name = c("X", "Y", "M", "U")))
ggdag(dag) + theme_dag_blank() + labs(title = "Causal model")

2. Create data set

Lets now create a data set with linear relationships:

N <- 10e3
u <- rnorm(n = N, mean = 0, sd = 1)
x <- 5*u + rnorm(n = N, mean = 0, sd = 1) * 2
m <- -0.2*x + rnorm(n = N, mean = 0, sd = 1) * 0.5
y <- 10*u - 3*m + rnorm(n = N, mean = 0, sd = 1) * 5
df <- tibble(x = x, y = y, u = u, z = z)

All variables should have a normal distribution.
Lets take a look:

map(df, ~ ggplot() + geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = .)))
$x

$y

$u

$z

Lets see the relationships between variables:

ggplot(data = df) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x, y))

ggplot(data = df) + geom_point(mapping = aes(z, x))

ggplot(data = df) + geom_point(mapping = aes(u, x))

ggplot(data = df) + geom_point(mapping = aes(u, y))

3. Try to estimate the influence of X on Y

Without access to M or U data. This should fail. We know a confounder exists between X and Y, but we dont have data of the confounder variable U:

linear_model <- lm(y ~ x, data = df)
summary(linear_model)

Call:
lm(formula = y ~ x, data = df)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
-22.5065  -4.3184   0.0379   4.3976  24.9683 

Coefficients:
             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)

x            2.332408   0.011918 195.709   <2e-16 ***

Residual standard error: 6.448 on 9998 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.793, Adjusted R-squared:  0.793 
F-statistic: 3.83e+04 on 1 and 9998 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The model says that for each 1 unit increment in x, y increases by 2.3 units (the real value is 0.6).

4. Try to estimate the influence of X on Y using M

What if we dont have data of the confounder variable, but we know and can measure the mediator M? The theory says we should be able to retrieve the real relationship between X and Y. Lets check it:

linear_model_mx <- lm(m ~ x, data = df)
summary(linear_model_mx)

Call:
lm(formula = m ~ x, data = df)

Residuals:
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-1.8158 -0.3262 -0.0007  0.3298  1.9155 

Coefficients:
              Estimate Std. Error  t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept) -0.0069696  0.0049244   -1.415    0.157    
x           -0.2002280  0.0009102 -219.989   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Residual standard error: 0.4924 on 9998 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.8288,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.8288 
F-statistic: 4.839e+04 on 1 and 9998 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
linear_model_ym <- lm(y ~ m + x, data = df)
summary(linear_model_ym)

Call:
lm(formula = y ~ m + x, data = df)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
-24.4808  -4.1795   0.0305   4.2483  23.5078 

Coefficients:
            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept) -0.03117    0.06245  -0.499    0.618    
m           -3.26310    0.12683 -25.729   <2e-16 ***
x            1.67904    0.02789  60.193   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Residual standard error: 6.245 on 9997 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.8059,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.8058 
F-statistic: 2.075e+04 on 2 and 9997 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

For each 1 unit increase in x, m decreases by 0.2 units. Thats exactly the real relationship!

For each 1 unit increase in m, y decreases by 3.26 units.

All the effect of X on Y passes through M:

Y = r_ym * M + r_yu * U + u_y = r_ym * (r_mx * X) + r_yu * U + u_y

So the effect of X on Y should be:

r_yx = r_ym * r_mx = -0.2 * -3.26 = 0.652

The real value is 0.6, so thats a much better result!! :)

5. Try to estimate the influence of X on Y using U

We already know this works (we checked it in previous experiments). But lets check it again:

linear_model_uxy <- lm(y ~ x + u)
summary(linear_model_uxy)

Call:
lm(formula = y ~ x + u)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
-18.8201  -3.4745   0.0578   3.5336  21.0414 

Coefficients:
            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept) -0.02500    0.05248  -0.476    0.634    
x            0.59514    0.02619  22.719   <2e-16 ***
u           10.10150    0.14149  71.395   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Residual standard error: 5.248 on 9997 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.8629,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.8629 
F-statistic: 3.146e+04 on 2 and 9997 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Perfect result, as expected! :)

6. Conclusions

  • Mediator variables are a good way to obtain the real relationship between confounded variables when we dont have data of the confounder variable U.

  • When the relationships are linear, the effect of X on Y can be calculated as r_yx = r_ym * r_mx
